                  high frequency, ultra short pulses) opens new
                  possibilities for measurement and thus has renewed
                  the interest on these observables, especially for
                  the analysis of various dynamical scenarios, well
                  beyond a simple access to electronic density of
                  states.  This, in turn, has motivated many
                  theoretical investigations of the dynamics of
                  electronic emission for molecules and clusters up to
                  such a complex and interesting system as C$_{60}$.
                  A theoretical tool of choice is here Time Dependent
                  Density Functional Theory (TDDFT) propagated in real
                  time and on a spatial grid, and augmented by a
                  Self-Interaction Correction (SIC).  This provides a
                  pertinent, robust, and efficient description of
                  electronic emission including the detailed pattern
                  of PES and PAD.  A direct comparison between
                  experiments and well founded elaborate microscopic
                  theories is thus readily possible, at variance with
                  more demanding observables such as for example
                  fragmentation or dissociation cross sections.  
                  The  purpose of this review is to describe the
                  theoretical tools developed on the basis of real
                  time and real space TDDFT to address in a realistic
                  manner the analysis of electronic emission following
                  irradiation of clusters and molecules by various
                  laser pulses.  After a general introduction, we
                  shall in a first part present the available
                  experimental results motivating such studies,
                  starting from the simplest total ionization signals
                  to the more elaborate PES and PAD, possibly
                  combining them and/or resolving them in time. This
                  experimental discussion will be complemented in a
                  second part by a presentation of available
                  theoretical tools focusing on TDDFT and detailing
                  the methods used to address ionization observables.
                  We shall also discuss the shortcomings of standard
                  versions of TDDFT, especially what concerns the SIC
                  problem, and show how to formally and practically
                  improve the theory on that aspect. A long third part
                  will be devoted to representative results. We shall
                  illustrate the use of total ionization in pump and
                  probe scenarios for tracking ionic dynamics in
                  clusters. PES and PAD will allow to more directly
                  address electronic dynamics itself. We shall in
                  particular discuss the impact of the dynamical
                  regime on PES and PAD.  When possible, the results
                  will be directly compared to experiments.  We shall
                  end this third part by a discussion on the
                  information content of energy/angular spectra of
                  emitted electrons in case of excitation by swift and
                  highly charged ions rather than lasers. The fourth
                  part of the paper will be devoted to future
                  directions of investigations.  From the rich choice
                  of developments, we shall in particular address two
                  aspects.  The first one concerns the account of
                  dissipative effects in TDDFT to be able to consider
                  longer laser pulses where the competition between
                  direct electron emission and thermalization is known
                  to play a role as, e.g., in experiments with
                  C$_{60}$.  Although such questions have been
                  superficially addressed in the simple case of
                  alkaline clusters by means of semi-classical
                  methods, no satisfying quantum formulation,
                  compulsory for most realistic systems, is yet
                  available. The second aspect concerns pump and probe
                  scenarios with attosecond lasers. The challenge is
                  there more on the capability to define proper
                  signals to be measured/computed at such a short time
                  scale. The TDDFT analysis provides here a valuable
                  tool in the search for the most efficient
                  observables. First encouraging results will be
                  presented on that occasion. We shall finally give a
                  short conclusion.  }
}
 
 
@article{Wop14b,
  title =   {Towards a realistic theoretical description of $\mathbf{C}_\mathbf{60}$ photoelectron momentum imaging experiments using {TDDFT}},
  author =  {P.~Wopperer and C. Z. Gao and T.~Barillot and C.~Cauchy 
             and A.~Marciniak and V.~Despr\'e and V.~Loriot and G.~Celep 
             and C.~Bordas and F. L\'epine and P. M. Dinh and E.~Suraud 
             and P.-G.~Reinhard},
  journal = {preprint 2014, subm. Phys. Rev. A},
  volume =  {},                                 
  year =    {},
  pages =   {},
  abstract= { We have studied theoretical photoelectron momentum
                  distributions of $\csixty$ using Time-Dependent
                  Density Functional Theory (TDDFT) with
                  self-interaction correction. Our calculations
                  include orientation averaging allowing a direct
                  comparison with experimental results. Two very
                  different photo-excitation conditions are
                  considered: excitation with high frequency XUV light
                  at 20~eV and with a low frequency IR femtosecond
                  pulse at 1.55~eV. The interaction with the XUV light
                  leads to a one-photon transition and linear
                  ionization regime. In that situation, the spectrum
                  of occupied single electron states in $\csixty$ is
                  directly mapped to the photoelectron spectrum. On
                  the contrary, the IR pulse leads to multiphoton
                  ionization in which only the two least bound states
                  contribute to the process. Calculated and
                  experimental angle-resolved photoelectron spectra
                  compare fairly well. The observed discrepancies can
                  be understood by the theoretical underestimation of
                  higher order many-body interaction processes such as
                  electron-electron scattering. These results pave the
                  way to a multiscale description of the $\csixty$
                  ionization mechanisms that is required to render
                  justice to the variety of processes observed
                  experimentally for fullerene molecules.  }
}


@article{Del98a,
